results.name: Number of orbits of the group of units of Z/(n) acting naturally on the 2-subsets of Z/(n).
example: a(3) = 2 since when U(3) = {1,2} acts naturally on the three 2-subsets {0,1}, {0,2}, {1,2} of Z/(3) the orbits are {{0,1},{0,2}} and {{1,2}}. Note that 2{0,1} = {0,2} but there is no unit a in U(3) such that a{0,1} = {1,2}.
results.author: _W. Edwin Clark_, Jul 15 2001
